{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.97,0,0,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74592"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9054"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60084"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7191"},{"type":"tags","id":"7192"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21531"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74592"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old gentleman who was the passenger in a motorvehicle accident presents to the Emergency Department. Secondary survey found clear fluid from his nostrils and that he had lost his sense of smell.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves exits through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olfactory nerve","Optic nerve","Oculomotor nerve","Trochlear nerve","Trigeminal nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eolfactory nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN I) consists of multiple small nerve fibres that pass through tiny foramina in the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone. These nerve fibres connect the olfactory receptors in the nasal mucosa to the olfactory bulb in the anterior cranial fossa. The clinical scenario describes a likely basilar skull fracture involving the cribriform plate, resulting in anosmia and cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN II) exits the skull through the optic canal, which is located in the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN III) passes through the superior orbital fissure to enter the orbit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN IV) also passes through the superior orbital fissure to enter the orbit. It is the only cranial nerve that exits from the dorsal aspect of the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN V) has three main branches. The ophthalmic division (V1) passes through the superior orbital fissure, the maxillary division (V2) through the foramen rotundum, and the mandibular division (V3) through the foramen ovale.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The olfactory nerve (CN I) exits through multiple small foramina in the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone.","The roof of the nasal cavity is formed by the cribriform plate which allows passage of olfactory nerve fibres from the nasal mucosa to the olfactory bulb.","Damage to the cribriform plate (e.g., in basilar skull fractures) can lead to anosmia and CSF rhinorrhoea."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Helwany M, Bordoni B. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 1 (Olfactory). 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310511."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60084"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60084"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T17:13:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T17:14:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9054"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74592"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"